e9fi Media Group]]|language=fr|access-date=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320185832/https://defimedia.info/achats-dans-les-supermarches-ne-cedez-pas-la-panique-lance-le-ministre-sawmynaden|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"panic2\">{{Cite news|url=https://defimedia.info/jayen-chellum-ne-cedez-pas-la-panique|title=Jayen Chellum : \"Ne c\u00e9dez pas \u00e0 la panique\"|date=19 March 2020|work=[[Le D\u00e9fi Media Group]]|language=fr|access-date=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320192650/https://defimedia.info/jayen-chellum-ne-cedez-pas-la-panique|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Legal===\n* On 19 March 2020, the following notices, order and regulations were published in the Government Gazette:\n\n:* The Ministry of Health was of the view that Mauritius appeared to be threatened with, or infected by the coronavirus and notice was given that sections 79 to 83 of the Public Health Act shall apply to Mauritius;<ref name=\"GovGa\">{{Cite news|url=http://pmo.govmu.org/English/Documents/28_Extra_Ord_190320.pdf|title=THE GOVERNMENT GAZETTE OF MAURITIUS No. 28|date=19 March 2020|work=Prime Minister Office|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n:* The Quarantine (Quarantinable Diseases) Regulations 2020 were published.<ref name=\"QUA\">{{Cite news|url=http://pmo.govmu.org/English/Documents/57_The%20Quarantaine%20_Quarantinable%20Diseases.pdf|title=THE QUARANTINE ACT Regulations made by the Minister under section 4(1)(a) and (b) of the Quarantine Act|date=19 March 2020|work=Prime Minister Office|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n:* The Ministry of Health gave order under sections 79 to 83 of the Public Health Act to prohibit the conveyance, excluding any conveyance transporting goods, from entering the territory of Mauritius as from 10:00 am on 19th March 2020 for a period of 15 days under Regulation 3 of The Quarantine (Quarantinable Diseases) Regulations 2020.<ref name=\"GovGa\"/>\n:* The Ministry of Health gave an order under Regulation 5 of The Quarantine (Quarantinable Diseases) Regulations 2020, prohibiting any passenger, excluding crew members, from boarding or disembarking from a conveyance as from 10:00 am on 19th March 2020 for a period of 15 days.<ref name=\"GovGa\"/>\n\n* The Prevention and Mitigation of Infectious Disease (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020 were published in the Government Gazette on 20 March 2020. Any person who contravenes the regulations shall, on conviction, be liable to a fine not exceeding MUR 500 and to imprisonment for a term not exceeding six months.<ref name=\"PMID\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.actogether.mu/media/11430/preven-1.pdf|title=Regulations made by the Minister under section 79 of the Public Health Act|date=20 March 2020|work=Acttogether|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> The regulation was amended on 22 March 2020.<ref name=\"PMID2\">{{Cite news|url=http://pmo.govmu.org/English/Documents/Communiqu%C3%A9%20and%20Reports/67_The%20Prevention%20and%20Mitigation%20of%20Infectious%20Disease%20(Coronavirus)%20(Amd)%20Regulations%202020.pdf|title=Regulations made by the Minister under section 79 of the Public Health Act|date=22 March 2020|work=Prime Minister Office|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* On 22 March 2020, the Curfew Order (General Notice No.512 of 2020) was issued by the Government of Mauritius, aimed at mitigating the spread of Covid-19 in Mauritius. The Curfew Order became effective as at 23 March 2020 at 20:00 hrs local time. Any person who contravenes the Curfew Order, shall on conviction, be liable to a fine not exceeding MUR 500 and to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 6 months.<ref name=\"CurfewOrder\">{{Cite news|url=http://pmo.govmu.org/English/Documents/Communiqu%C3%A9%20and%20Reports/31_Extra_Ord_220320.pdf|title=Curfew Order made by the Minister under regulation 14(1) of the Prevention and Mitigation of Infectious Disease (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020|work=Prime Minister Office|date=22 March 2020|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> On 30 March 2020, the Curfew Order was extended till 15 April 2020 at 20:00 hrs local time.<ref name=\"Govmu.org\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.govmu.org/English/News/Pages/PM-Sanitary-Curfew-to-be-extended-till-15th-April-2020-.aspx|title=PM: Sanitary Curfew to be extended till 15th April 2020|date=19 March 2020|work=[[Government Portal of Mauritius]]|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Travel and entry restrictions===\n* On 18 March 2020, the Mauritian Prime Minister announced that all passengers, including Mauritians and foreigners, would be prohibited from entering Mauritian territory for the next 15 days, which started at 6:00 GMT (10:10 am Mauritian time). Passengers wishing to leave Mauritius would be allowed to leave. Cargo airplanes and ships would also be allowed to enter the country.<ref name=\"Fourth\">{{Cite news|url=https://defimedia.info/coronavirus-aucun-passager-ne-sera-autorise-sur-le-territoire-mauricien-partir-de-ce-jeudi|title=Coronavirus : aucun passager ne sera autoris\u00e9 sur le territoire mauricien \u00e0 partir de ce jeudi|date=18 March 2020|work=[[Le D\u00e9fi Media Group]]|language=fr|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319183917/https://defimedia.info/coronavirus-aucun-passager-ne-sera-autorise-sur-le-territoire-mauricien-partir-de-ce-jeudi|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"bani\">{{Cite news|url=https://defimedia.info/trois-cas-positifs-au-covid-19-tout-passager-interdit-dacces-pendant-les-15-prochains-jours|title=Trois cas positifs au Covid-19 : tout passager interdit d'acc\u00e8s pendant les 15 prochains jours|date=19 March 2020|work=[[Le D\u00e9fi Media Group]]|language=fr|access-date=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320200136/https://defimedia.info/trois-cas-positifs-au-covid-19-tout-passager-interdit-dacces-pendant-les-15-prochains-jours|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Some Mauritians who were stranded in different airports around the world were allowed to enter  Mauritian territory on 22 March 2020. They were required to spend 14 days in isolation at different premises provided by the government.<ref name=\"Twelve\">{{Cite news|url=https://defimedia.info/laeroport-de-plaisance-quelque-300-mauriciens-venant-de-londres-et-mumbai-ont-ete-rapatries-indique-girish-appaya|title=L'a\u00e9roport de Plaisance : \" quelque 300 Mauriciens venant de Londres et Mumbai ont \u00e9t\u00e9 rapatri\u00e9s \", indique Girish Appaya|date=22 March 2020|work=[[Le D\u00e9fi Media Group]]|language=fr|access-date=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322091256/https://defimedia.info/laeroport-de-plaisance-quelque-300-mauriciens-venant-de-londres-et-mumbai-ont-ete-rapatries-indique-girish-appaya|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As at 2 April 2020, it was reported that 1,000 Mauritians were able to reach the island, while 1,721 Mauritians in more than 40 countries were stranded abroad and 615 Mauritians who live abroad expressed their wish to return.<ref name=\"Return\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.lexpress.mu/article/374022/coinces-letranger-1-721-mauriciens-bloques-dans-plus-40-pays|title=Coinc\u00e9s \u00e0 l'\u00e9tranger: 1 721 Mauriciens bloqu\u00e9s dans plus de 40 pays|date=2 April 2020|work=[[L'Express (Mauritius)]]|language=fr|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> On 5 April 2020, the Minister of Foreign Affairs reported that more than 3,000 Mauritians were stranded abroad.<ref name=\"astar\">{{Cite news|url=https://defimedia.info/covid-19-pas-moins-de-3-000-mauriciens-coinces-letranger-selon-le-ministre-bodha|title=Covid-19 - \" Pas moins de 3 000 Mauriciens coinc\u00e9s \u00e0 l'\u00e9tranger \" selon le ministre Bodha\n|date=5 April 2020|work=[[Le D\u00e9fi Media Group]]|language=fr|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Economic===\n* On 10 March 2020, the Monetary Policy Committee of the [[Bank of Mauritius]] reduced the Key Repo Rate (KRR) by 50 basis points to 2.85 per cent per annum. The decision  was mainly prompted by the will to stimulate domestic economic activity.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bom.mu/sites/default/files/bank_of_mauriitus_-_support_programme_-_13_march_2020_-_final.pdf|title=BANK OF MAURITIUS INTRODUCES A SUPPORT PROGRAMME TO ACCOMPANY LOCAL ECONOMIC OPERATORS IN COVID-19 CONTEXT|date=13 March 2020 |work=[[Bank of Mauritius]]}}</ref>\n\n* On 13 March 2020, the Ministry of Finance introduced several measures to assist companies with financial difficulties.<ref name=\"mof\">{{Cite news |url=http://mof.govmu.org/English/DOCUMENTS/PLAN%20DE%20SOUTIEN_13%20MARCH%202020.PDF|title=Plan de Soutien aux Entreprises|date=13 March 2020 |work=Ministry of Finance, Economic Planning and Development}}</ref> The Bank of Mauritius introduced a support programme consisting of five key measures to assist Mauritian businesses across all economic sectors. The measures included:<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n\n:* Special Relief amount of MUR 5 billion through commercial banks to meet cash flow and working capital requirements of economic operators directly impacted by Covid-19;\n:* The Bank of Mauritius reduced the Cash Reserve Ratio applicable to commercial banks from 9% to 8%. This reduction is a key measure that aims at supporting banks to further assist businesses which are being directly impacted by Covid-19;\n:* Commercial banks will provide a moratorium of six months on capital repayment for existing loans for economic operators that are being affected by Covid-19;\n:* The Bank of Mauritius has put on hold the Guideline on Credit Impairment Measurement and Income Recognition, which has been in effect since January 2020. This decision was taken to allow commercial banks to continue supporting enterprises facing cash flow and working capital difficulties in the context of Covid-19; and\n:* The Bank of Mauritius introduced a 2.5% Two-Year Bank of Mauritius 2020 Savings Bond for an amount of MUR 5.0 Billion from 23 March 2020. The Bond will be issued at par in multiples of MUR 25,000 to individuals who are residents of Mauritius and up to a maximum cumulative investment amount of MUR 1,000,000 per investor, whether singly or jointly, and to locally registered Non-Governmental Organisations running on a non-profit making basis for the same maximum investment amount of MUR 1,000,000.\n\n* On 22 March 2020, the [[Government of Mauritius]] announced the Wage Assistance Scheme to ensure that all employees in the private sector are duly paid their salary for the month of March 2020. The scheme concerns both Mauritians and foreign employees working in Mauritius. Every business in the private sector, in respect of the month of March 2020, will be entitled to receive an amount equivalent to the 15 days\u2019 basic wage bill for all of its employees drawing a monthly basic wage of up to MUR 50,000 subject to a cap of MUR 12,500 of assistance per employee.<ref name=\"scheme\">{{Cite news|url=https://defimedia.info/confinement-voici-tout-ce-que-vous-devrez-savoir-sur-le-wage-assistance-scheme|title=Confinement : voici tout ce que vous devrez savoir sur le Wage Assistance Scheme|date=23 March 2020|work=[[Le D\u00e9fi Media Group]]|language=fr|access-date=4 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324191258/https://defimedia.info/confinement-voici-tout-ce-que-vous-devrez-savoir-sur-le-wage-assistance-scheme|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"mof3\">{{Cite news |url=http://mof.govmu.org/English//DOCUMENTS/WAGE%20ASSISTANCE%20SCHEME.PDF|title=Government Wage Assistance Scheme for the Month of March 2020 to Private Sector Employees|date=23 March 2020 |work=Ministry of Finance, Economic Planning and Development}}</ref><ref name=\"mra\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.mra.mu/download/WageAssistanceScheme230320.pdf|title=Government Wage Assistance Scheme (GWAS)|date=23 March 2020 |work=Ministry of Finance, Economic Planning and Development}}</ref>\n\n* Further to its Support Programme on 13 March 2020, the Bank of Mauritius announced additional measures on 23 March 2020 to support households and businesses impacted financially by Covid-19, and to ensure that the domestic rupee and foreign exchange markets continue to operate smoothly. These measures are as follows:<ref name=\"BOM2\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bom.mu/sites/default/files/bank_of_mauritius_media_release_-_additional_measures_to_support_households_and_businesse_-_23_march_2020_0.pdf|title=BANK OF MAURITIUS COVID-19 SUPPORT PROGRAMME ADDITIONAL MEASURES TO SUPPORT HOUSEHOLDS AND BUSINESSES|date=23 March 2020 |work=[[Bank of Mauritius]]}}</ref>\n\n:* Mauritian households impacted by Covid-19 may request their commercial banks for a moratorium of six months on capital repayments on their existing household loans as from the 1st of April 2020. In addition, for households earning a combined monthly basic salary of up to MUR 50,000 the Bank of Mauritius will bear the interest payable for the period 1st of April 2020 to 30th of June 2020 on their outstanding household loans with commercial banks;\n:* The Bank of Mauritius introduced a Special Foreign Currency (USD) Line of Credit targeting operators having foreign currency earnings, including SMEs. This line of credit shall be for an amount of USD 300 million, to be made available through commercial banks. Funds will be made available to commercial banks at six-month USD Libor for this facility;\n:* The Bank of Mauritius introduced a USD/MUR swap arrangement with commercial banks for an initial amount of USD 100 million. This arrangement would enable commercial banks to support import-oriented businesses, except for the State Trading Corporation which will be dealing directly with the Bank of Mauritius for its foreign currency requirements; and\n:* During the national confinement period, fees applicable on shared ATM services were waived to enable customers to have access to the ATM of any bank regardless of the issuer of the card.\n\n* On 31 March 2020, the Government implemented a Self-Employed Assistance Scheme (SEAS) through the [[Mauritius Revenue Authority]] (MRA) to assist self-employed persons who have suffered a loss of revenue as a consequence of the lockdown in the fight against Covid-19.<ref name=\"MRA\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.mra.mu/index.php/media1/self-employed-assistance-scheme|title=COVID-19 SELF\u2013EMPLOYED ASSISTANCE SCHEME|date=31 March 2020 |work=[[Mauritius Revenue Authority]]}}</ref> Additional financial support was also provided to Micro, Small and Medium Enterprises.<ref name=\"EDB\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.edbmauritius.org/media/3121/support-to-sme-and-informal-sector.pdf|title=COVID \u2013 19 Assistance Scheme to the Informal Sector|date=31 March 2020 |work=[[Board of Investment (Mauritius)|Economic Development Board]]}}</ref>\n\n* To encourage public and enterprises to contribute to the Covid-19 Solidarity Fund, on 1 April 2020, the Ministry of Finance announced that he will allow them to deduct the amount donated/contributed from their taxable income.<ref name=\"sol\">{{Cite news|url=http://mof.govmu.org/English//DOCUMENTS/COMMUNIQUE_TAX%20DEDUCTION_DONATION%20SOLIDARITY%20FUND.PDF|title=Communique Contribution/Donation made to the COVID-19 Solidarity Fund|date=1 April 2020 |work=Ministry of Finance, Economic Planning and Development|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n===Doctors===\n* Mauritians were advised not to visit hospitals for minor issues. In this respect, Mauritian doctors set up a consultation service online named \u201cMauriDoc\u201d to give free medical opinions and advice.<ref name=\"Mauridoc\">{{Cite news|url=https://defisante.defimedia.info/maladies/mauridoc-un-service-de-teleconsultation-gratuite-mis-en-place/|title=MauriDoc : la liste des m\u00e9decins qui font de la t\u00e9l\u00e9consultation gratuite mise \u00e0 jour|date=5 April 2020|work=[[Le D\u00e9fi Media Group]]|language=fr|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nOn 6 April 2020, Mauritius became the first country to order the termination of all football leagues in the country for the 2019\u20132020 season.<ref name=\"goal\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/coronavirus-mauritius-terminates-football-season/1wz0obtlbt7js1uwi2y7xjd43x|title=Coronavirus: Mauritius terminates football season|date=6 April 2020|work=[[Goal (website)|Goal.com]]|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Economic impact ==\n* It is estimated that the shutdowns implemented to control the pandemic costs the Mauritian economy between [[Mauritian rupee|Rs]] 1 billion and Rs 1.3 billion a day. Resulting in a total estimated cost of Rs 15-20 billion or 4% of the country's GDP for the full 15 day lock-down announced by government on 20 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lexpress.mu/article/372973/covid-19-un-confinement-national-rs-1-milliard-jour|title=Covid-19: un confinement national \u00e0 Rs 1 milliard par jour|last=R\u00e9daction|first=La|date=21 March 2020|website=lexpress.mu|language=fr|access-date=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322183956/https://www.lexpress.mu/article/372973/covid-19-un-confinement-national-rs-1-milliard-jour|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 30 March 2020, the sanitary curfew which started on 23 March at 20 00 hours was extended for two weeks up to 15 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.govmu.org/English/News/Pages/PM-Sanitary-Curfew-to-be-extended-till-15th-April-2020-.aspx|title = Sanitary Curfew to be extended till 15th April 2020|work = [[Government Portal of Mauritius]]|date = 30 March 2020|access-date = 4 April 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200401055634/http://www.govmu.org/English/News/Pages/PM-Sanitary-Curfew-to-be-extended-till-15th-April-2020-.aspx|archive-date = 1 April 2020|url-status = live}}</ref> The lockdown was extended to Monday 04 May 2020, to further contain the spread of the Covid-19 in the country.<ref name=\"govmuorg22\"/>\n* On 22 April, the board of [[Air Mauritius]] took the decision to place the Company under voluntary administration after coronavirus-related disruptions made it impossible for the airline to meet its financial obligations for the foreseeable future. The pandemic had a major impact on the revenue of the company while it was seeking to change its business model to address existing financial problems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://defimedia.info/breaking-news-air-mauritius-placee-sous-administration-volontaire|title=[Breaking News] Air Mauritius plac\u00e9e sous administration volontaire|date=22 April 2020|website=[[Le D\u00e9fi Media Group]]|language=fr|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]]\n* [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa]]\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on aviation and tourism]]\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education]]\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion]]\n* [[Impact of the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic on politics]]\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports]]\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Mauritius}}\n* [http://www.covid19.mu/ covid19.mu] - Official Coronavirus website from the Ministry of Health\n* [https://besafemoris.mu/ beSafeMoris.mu] - Official Coronavirus APP for Mauritians\n*[https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6 gisanddata.maps] - Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases\n*[https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ Worldometer, COVID-19 coronavirus pandemic] \u2013 Confirmed Cases and Deaths